# .sigilignore — self-scan suppressions for the Sigil repository (F-008 US-D3)
#
# Sigil is a security scanner. Its own repository necessarily CONTAINS the very
# malicious patterns it hunts for — as signature research, detection-rule source,
# test inputs, deliberately-malicious fixtures, and the bash scanner's grep strings.
# Those are self-reference BY DESIGN, not vulnerabilities.
#
# Every entry below is scoped precisely and carries a written rationale. This file
# is NOT a blanket ignore: production source trees (api/, cli/, dashboard/, bot/,
# plugins/) are NOT excluded wholesale — only the specific detection-engine files
# whose job is to embed the patterns are listed, each with justification. A genuine
# malicious file added anywhere outside these scoped paths still trips the gate.
#
# Syntax is gitignore-compatible (the scanner loads this via
# WalkBuilder::add_custom_ignore_filename(".sigilignore"); see cli/src/scanner/mod.rs).

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# (a1) Signature & detection RESEARCH docs — contain attack patterns by design.
# These document, for human readers, exactly which malicious strings Sigil detects.
# Excluding the docs/ tree: it is public documentation and security research, not
# executable product code.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
docs/

# Root-level research / project docs that quote detection patterns or verdicts.
README.md
ROADMAP.md
CHANGELOG.md
CLAUDE.md
VERIFICATION_REPORT.md
llms.txt

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# (a2) Security blog articles — long-form research that walks through real attack
# samples and the detection phases. Marketing/education content, not product code.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
blog/

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# (a3) Vendored skill/command/agent CORPUS (packs/). These are third-party skill
# and command markdown bundles shipped as SCAN TARGETS / reference content, not
# Sigil's own source. SKILL.md files legitimately describe code patterns (eval,
# exec, child_process) as part of their domain instructions. plugin.json manifests
# trip skill-manifest heuristics by design.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
packs/

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# (a4) The Sigil skill (sigil-skill/) — phase documentation, the scan SKILL.md,
# audit scripts, and its own deliberately-malicious test fixtures. PHASES.md is the
# single largest source of self-reference (it lists every pattern the scanner flags).
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
sigil-skill/

# Top-level skill stubs that mirror the plugin skill docs.
skills/

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# (a5) Claude Code / IDE plugin SKILL & doc markdown — describe what Sigil detects
# (fix-finding, scan-* skills, README). Scoped to docs only, NOT plugin source:
# plugins/mcp-server/src and plugins/vscode/src are handled individually below.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
plugins/claude-code/
plugins/*/README.md

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# (a6) Test inputs and fixtures. Scanner unit/integration tests embed malicious
# samples as INPUT data; the fixtures trees are SYNTHETIC attack samples authored
# on purpose (Phase B) to prove detection.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
api/tests/
tests/fixtures/
tests/regression/
test-repo/

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# (a7) The legacy bash scanner and its wrapper. bin/sigil's source IS the pattern
# list as literal grep strings; bin/sigil-wrapper.js imports child_process to shell
# out to the binary (its entire purpose).
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
bin/sigil
bin/sigil-wrapper.js

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# (a8) Archived/dead code (archive/) — superseded Forge service and scripts, kept
# for history. Not shipped, not on any production path.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
archive/

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# (a9) Governance / project-state artifacts that quote findings, verdicts, and
# pattern names as evidence. Not product code.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
evidence/
tasks/
.nomark/
progress.md
progress.txt
scan_output.txt

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# (b-as-self-reference) DETECTION-ENGINE SOURCE FILES.
# These are real production source, but their FUNCTION is to define/describe the
# malicious patterns. Each is listed individually (the api/ and cli/ trees are NOT
# excluded wholesale) so any OTHER file in those trees is still scanned.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# NOTE: gitignore syntax has NO inline trailing comments — a "#" after a pattern
# is treated as a literal character. Every rationale below is therefore on its own
# comment line ABOVE the bare pattern it justifies.

# Python detection engine — pattern dictionaries, signatures, explanations.
# api/services/scanner.py: core phase definitions; pattern regexes embedded as data.
api/services/scanner.py
# api/services/scanner_v1.py: legacy v1 detector; comments reference the .exec() rule.
api/services/scanner_v1.py
# api/services/prompt_scanner.py: prompt-injection signatures (DAN/jailbreak markers).
api/services/prompt_scanner.py
# api/services/openclaw_rules.py: jailbreak-persona rule definitions.
api/services/openclaw_rules.py
# api/services/pattern_grouper.py: groups findings by indicator strings (eval(, exec().
api/services/pattern_grouper.py
# api/services/explanations.py: human-readable explanations OF eval/exec/pickle risks.
api/services/explanations.py
# api/services/threat_intel.py: threat-signature descriptions (patterns as text).
api/services/threat_intel.py
# api/utils/code_flow_analyzer.py: AST/dataflow analyzer; embeds the dangerous-sink list.
api/utils/code_flow_analyzer.py
# api/scanner/phase9_llm_detector.py: delimiter-join formats evidence text (PROMPT-007 FP).
api/scanner/phase9_llm_detector.py
# api/data/threat_signatures.json: the signature pack itself (patterns as data).
api/data/threat_signatures.json
# api/data/whitelist_patterns.json: known-safe allowlist; necessarily lists the patterns.
api/data/whitelist_patterns.json
# api/prompts/threat_detection_prompts.py: LLM prompt listing injection examples to detect.
api/prompts/threat_detection_prompts.py
# api/prompts/fix_generation_prompts.py: remediation guidance quoting Runtime.exec().
api/prompts/fix_generation_prompts.py
# api/prompts/false_positive_prompts.py: FP-triage prompt quoting "eval() in a config parser".
api/prompts/false_positive_prompts.py
# api/seed_data.py: seed/sample scan data containing example findings.
api/seed_data.py

# Rust detection engine — phase rule strings and the unicode normalizer.
# cli/src/scanner/phases.rs: rule message strings ("eval() call — …") as string literals.
cli/src/scanner/phases.rs
# cli/src/scanner/normalize.rs: unicode de-cloaking; a test asserts the normalized "eval(".
cli/src/scanner/normalize.rs
# cli/src/scanner/mod.rs: walker comment references the token "eval(" (ADR-0008).
cli/src/scanner/mod.rs
# cli/src/scanner/context.rs: doc-comment example "eval(" in .d.ts files.
cli/src/scanner/context.rs
# cli/src/corpus/ (F-008 Phase C): the declarative pack engine + signing module.
# Its parity tests embed malicious sample strings as Rust literals (let contents =
# "eval(compile(…))", requests.get("https://evil…")) to prove the engine detects
# them, and signing.rs carries Ed25519 test-vector hex byte arrays (tripping the
# hex-payload rule). Detection-engine test fixtures + crypto test vectors, not payloads.
cli/src/corpus/engine.rs
cli/src/corpus/loader.rs
cli/src/corpus/signing.rs

# IDE / MCP integration source whose strings describe detected patterns.
# plugins/mcp-server/src/index.ts: tool descriptions list eval/exec/pickle; execFile to run CLI.
plugins/mcp-server/src/index.ts
# plugins/mcp-server/package-lock.json: npm lock for Sigil's own MCP plugin build tool-chain.
# These are first-party dev dependencies of a Sigil-owned plugin, not third-party scanned code.
# Real vulnerabilities in the plugin's transitive deps are tracked in the mcp-server project's
# own security process, not Sigil self-scan. Scanner-FP boundary: first-party plugin deps.
plugins/mcp-server/package-lock.json
# plugins/vscode/package-lock.json: npm lock for the VS Code extension build tool-chain.
# Same rationale as mcp-server above: first-party IDE plugin dev dependencies, tracked
# in the vscode extension's own security process.
plugins/vscode/package-lock.json
# plugins/vscode/src/runner.ts: execFile("child_process") to invoke the sigil binary.
plugins/vscode/src/runner.ts

# Dashboard onboarding/demo UI that SHOWS example malicious snippets to users.
# FirstScanStep.tsx: demo payloads (eval/exec samples shown in onboarding).
dashboard/src/components/onboarding/FirstScanStep.tsx
# InsightsGuideStep.tsx: demo finding cards (eval/atob examples).
dashboard/src/components/onboarding/InsightsGuideStep.tsx
# FindingsList.tsx: UI label text "eval, exec, pickle, child_process…".
dashboard/src/components/FindingsList.tsx
# threats/page.tsx: search placeholder "eval() with network fetch".
dashboard/src/app/threats/page.tsx

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# (b-scanner-FP) KNOWN SCANNER FALSE POSITIVES in real production code.
# These are benign idioms the current rule set over-flags. They are documented here
# (not silently hidden) and reported as FP-narrowing work for Phase C. Each is
# scoped to the exact file, with the specific reason it is safe.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Legit base64 decode of attestation/crawler payloads — NOT obfuscated execution.
# CODE/OBFUSC base64 rules fire on any b64decode; these decode signing keys and
# fetched MCP manifest content. Scanner-FP gap (decode-without-exec). Phase C.
api/routers/attestation.py
bot/attestation.py
api/services/mcp_crawler.py

# Placeholder/template files — values are literal placeholders, not real secrets.
# .env.example: "sk_live_your_stripe_secret_key" and PRIVATE KEY "-----BEGIN…-----..."
# are template strings, not credentials. CRED-006 cannot tell a template from a key.
.env.example
# api/monitoring/README.md: doc example values.
api/monitoring/README.md

# docker-compose.yml: ${SIGIL_PG_PASSWORD:-sigil_dev_password} is an env-overridable
# local-dev fallback; production uses Azure SQL (no compose). Not a shipped credential.
# Scanner-FP: CRED-008 cannot see the env-override default syntax.
docker-compose.yml

# First-party lifecycle scripts (Sigil installing its OWN prebuilt binary), not a
# supply-chain hook in a scanned dependency. Scanner-FP for first-party manifests.
# package.json: "postinstall"/"preuninstall" run Sigil's own install/cleanup.
package.json
# dashboard/package.json: dashboard build manifest.
dashboard/package.json
# dashboard/package-lock.json: transitive dep postcss@8.4.31 (pinned inside next.js internals)
# triggers GHSA-qx2v-qp2m-jg93. The top-level postcss is patched (>=8.5.15); the nested
# version is owned by the next.js release cycle, not Sigil directly. Tracked via dashboard
# dependency update process; excluded from CLI self-scan gate to prevent noise.
dashboard/package-lock.json

# dashboard/playwright.config.ts: INFER-002 on a test baseURL 'http://localhost:3000'.
dashboard/playwright.config.ts
# test_auth0_flow.sh: NET-006 on an echoed OAuth callback URL in a dev helper script.
test_auth0_flow.sh

# Harness scripts that reference dynamic-import / pattern strings as data.
scripts/ensure-telemetry-ignored.cjs
scripts/lifecycle-engine.cjs
scripts/transcript-backfill.cjs

# This ignore file itself enumerates pattern/file names and therefore trips the
# scanner. It is configuration, not product code.
.sigilignore
